Perhaps the department in which modern editors have added most, as it is the one which has had the most attractions to me, has been that of tracing in the several poems the sequence and proportion of the thoughts. This is a function of criticism to which every reader with any imagination thinks himself equal; and he is apt to resent what seem to him the superfluous, if not prosaic and inadequate‚ com- ments of another mind. A commentator on a poet so loved and familiar as Horace is, at any rate to the elder generation among us, must make his count for such resentment He would only attempt in part to disarm it, by pleading that as he has ven- tured at times to set aside the interpretations of his predecessors, so he is quite prepared ¹that his own interpretations should be set aside by others: that it is the purpose and the method‚ not the particular conclusionS‚ to which he attaches value. The thoughts even osa lyrical poem do not follow one another at haphazard. lf the links be forged by feeling rather than by logic, yet the feelings must be such as can be traced‚ and the mind cannot be really in sympathy with the poem unless consciously or unconsciously it follows them.
